### Description

In some scenarios it could be useful to import some modules dynamically without bundling by @angular/compiler

### Proposed solution

We could use function that would allow to import ES modules.

``` TS
import { importExternal, Injectable } from '@angular/core';

@Injectable()
export class ScriptsService {
  load() {
    return importExternal('./prebuild/my-lib.esm.js');
  }
}
```

### Alternatives considered

Currently we are able to achieve this in two ways:

1. By using `<script>`
``` TS
import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';

@Injectable()
export class ScriptsService {
  load() {
    const script = document.body.appendChild(document.createElement('script'));
    script.type = 'module';
    script.src = './prebuild/my-lib.esm.js';
    return new Promise((resolve) => {
      script.onload = resolve;
    });
  }
}
```

2. By using `webpackIgnore`
``` TS
import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';

@Injectable()
export class ScriptsService {
  load() {
    // @ts-ignore
    return import(/* webpackIgnore: true */ './prebuild/my-lib.esm.js');
  }
}
```

Consider a typed group for storing contact information:

```
declare interface ContactControls {
	name: FormControl<string|null>;
}

contactForm: FormGroup<ContactControls> = ...;

saveForm(form: FormGroup<ContactControls>) {
	service.newContact(contactForm.value);
}
```

What should be the type of `newContact`? The answer, of course, is the value type:

```
declare interface Contact {
	name: string|null;
}

class ContactService {
	newContact(c: Contact) {}
}
```

This is quite redundant, and therefore, we should allow the value type to be generated automatically. (Or possibly the other way around, which is more generally useful, but a bit trickier to implement.) We already have the helper types to do this, but we need to do some additional design work in order to expose them publicly.

